The paper deals with algorithms for computing maximum matching in graphs, which is a fundamental problem in graph theory and has applications in various fields. The use of the term "local computation" suggests that the algorithm is designed to work efficiently in a distributed or parallel computing setting, which falls under the category of cs.DS (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing). The algorithm also involves polylogarithmic time complexity, which is a common feature of algorithms in cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry). The problem of maximum matching is closely related to graph theory and combinatorial optimization, which are covered in cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis).
